WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.220
Hi everyone, my name's Toph, I use he and they pronouns, and I'm a software engineer

00:00:05.220 --> 00:00:11.560
on Connect. And today I'm going to be talking about the Connect Gallery. I'm going to be

00:00:11.560 --> 00:00:16.320
showing you some of the extensions that you can find there.

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:20.120
So I'm pretty sure that most people in the room know what Connect is, but just so we're

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:25.920
all on the same page, Connect is a data science publishing or deployment platform that we

00:00:25.920 --> 00:00:32.919
develop here at Posit. You can deploy your data science work, so applications, dashboards,

00:00:32.919 --> 00:00:42.720
reports, APIs, that kind of thing, and share it with stakeholders, maybe in your organization.

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:49.959
And the gallery is a new home on Connect for example content and for extensions.

00:00:49.959 --> 00:00:54.320
And something I'm going to be using as sort of a framing device for this is that maintaining

00:00:54.320 --> 00:01:00.480
long-lived apps is kind of tricky. And by this I mean like the things that we publish

00:01:00.480 --> 00:01:06.040
to Connect that like stick around and we don't just share once but become part of our organization's

00:01:06.040 --> 00:01:12.800
infrastructure. So some of the extensions in the gallery are designed to like help with

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:17.879
some of the friction of this. And I'm going to go through those.

00:01:17.879 --> 00:01:23.120
So one of the challenges with maintaining long-lived apps is kind of knowing what's

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:29.599
important. So like getting a message like this, getting a Slack message from someone

00:01:29.599 --> 00:01:35.879
saying that they are checking a dashboard that we published is very validating. It means

00:01:35.879 --> 00:01:41.000
the work that I am doing is having impact, but it's just an anecdote and we really want

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:50.000
data, right? There's some data on usage already in Connect, it turns out. It's here in the

00:01:50.040 --> 00:01:56.320
content settings pane. But this isn't really helpful for comparing across bits of content.

00:01:56.320 --> 00:02:03.320
So in the gallery here, you would go down and install a usage metrics dashboard. I will

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:15.759
say by the way, this is Builder's live demo. There will be a live demo later, don't worry.

00:02:16.080 --> 00:02:21.360
But I also have some screen recordings. And so in the usage metrics dashboard, you can

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:28.360
see all of your published content, so apps, APIs, et cetera, and data on their usage.

00:02:29.919 --> 00:02:36.360
And there are some controls in the sidebar. So I can filter for different content types

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:42.320
or time periods or narrow the scope to just the things that I've published. And then I

00:02:42.320 --> 00:02:49.320
can dive in to a detail view for a specific piece of important content to see who's viewing

00:02:51.720 --> 00:02:58.639
it and when they're looking at it. So this hopefully helps us get a better sense of where

00:02:58.639 --> 00:03:05.639
to spend our time and energy when we're thinking about maintaining things that we have on Connect.

00:03:06.039 --> 00:03:11.960
So there are other types of Slack messages that we might get that motivate maintenance

00:03:11.960 --> 00:03:18.919
tasks. We don't always want to get a message saying that something's down, but downtime

00:03:18.919 --> 00:03:24.800
does happen. And in this case, I would go and have to fix that dashboard. But no one

00:03:24.800 --> 00:03:30.279
really wants a notification like this. I would much rather be the first person to know if

00:03:30.279 --> 00:03:35.479
something that I'm responsible for goes down. And so we have a content health monitor, which

00:03:35.479 --> 00:03:42.479
you can point at a specific important piece of content on Connect, and it'll check to

00:03:45.199 --> 00:03:51.039
see if it's reachable. Or you can have it run on a schedule and send you an email if

00:03:51.039 --> 00:03:58.039
that thing becomes unreachable. I'll walk through setting this up a little bit later.

00:03:59.039 --> 00:04:04.039
So another thing that we need to deal with is making sure that stuff's up to date. Now,

00:04:04.039 --> 00:04:10.000
I don't know about you, but I know that I updated to a newer version of Python at some

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:16.880
point, and I've definitely updated some of the things on Connect since I updated Python.

00:04:16.880 --> 00:04:21.700
So those things might be running Python 3.10, but there's sort of this dark matter of other

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:25.799
things on Connect that might be running Python 3.9, and if it's removed from the server,

00:04:25.799 --> 00:04:30.640
I don't want them to go down. And so the question is, like, do I have to look at each

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:37.760
one to figure out which version of Python is running on the server? Turns out, so there's

00:04:37.760 --> 00:04:44.760
an extension in the gallery called the Runtime Version Scanner. And the Runtime Version Scanner,

00:04:45.519 --> 00:04:51.440
you can look at the runtimes that different bits of, that you can see all of the stuff

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:56.720
that you've published to Connect. You can pick a version of R, Python, and or Quarto

00:04:56.720 --> 00:05:03.720
from a dropdown menu, and then see just the things that are running that version or lower.

00:05:05.399 --> 00:05:12.000
And you can also see the view count over a time period that you can select. And so that

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.820
can help you prioritize the most important things and maybe highlight some things that

00:05:15.859 --> 00:05:21.779
you can just delete and not have to worry about.

00:05:21.779 --> 00:05:28.420
So one other type of maintenance task here is accounting for vulnerabilities. And I often

00:05:28.420 --> 00:05:32.940
just don't have much ambient awareness at all of if there are any vulnerabilities in

00:05:32.940 --> 00:05:37.100
the packages that I'm using. Like if I'm working on something new and I'm setting it up, like,

00:05:37.100 --> 00:05:43.700
I'll install the latest version of, you know, FastAPI or something, but I'm not necessarily

00:05:43.739 --> 00:05:48.339
going to update that whenever I'm updating this, you know, this dashboard that I'm working

00:05:48.339 --> 00:05:53.980
on, because that could cause a bug or, you know, introduces more busy work.

00:05:53.980 --> 00:05:58.140
And so I guess there are two problems here. The first problem is just which of the things

00:05:58.140 --> 00:06:05.059
that I've got on Connect is running the version that has the vulnerability? And then just

00:06:05.059 --> 00:06:11.019
in general, how can I monitor to see if there is anything running a vulnerability? So you

00:06:11.019 --> 00:06:14.940
may be detecting a pattern here. There's a package vulnerability scanner that we have

00:06:14.940 --> 00:06:22.059
up in the gallery. And the package vulnerability scanner lets you see which of your, the things

00:06:22.059 --> 00:06:28.579
that you've published to Connect has a package which has a reported vulnerability. We actually

00:06:28.579 --> 00:06:34.179
pull in vulnerability data on packages from Posit Package Manager. And you can also dive

00:06:34.260 --> 00:06:41.019
into an individual piece of content to see details on the vulnerability itself, as well

00:06:41.019 --> 00:06:47.540
as the version of the package that it was fixed in. So now, looking at this, I'll know

00:06:47.540 --> 00:06:54.179
which bits of content I need to go update and what version of the package to update

00:06:54.179 --> 00:06:59.540
to. And even without getting a notification from someone, I can come check this to see

00:06:59.540 --> 00:07:06.019
if there are any vulnerabilities on Connect in my content.

00:07:06.019 --> 00:07:12.820
And so just to take a quick look back, the four extensions that I've described, which

00:07:12.820 --> 00:07:21.339
are to do with package, with, I guess, maintenance of long-running apps. We've got a usage metrics

00:07:21.339 --> 00:07:26.980
dashboard, which helps us understand what's most important. We've got a content health

00:07:26.980 --> 00:07:32.140
monitor, which lets us pick an important piece of content and get alerts if it goes

00:07:32.140 --> 00:07:38.739
down. And then we have two, the runtime version scanner and the package vulnerability scanner,

00:07:38.739 --> 00:07:46.420
which help with those maintenance tasks. So I'm going to show you some of this live on

00:07:46.420 --> 00:07:54.059
a Connect, on a Connect server. Let me get my mouse cursor over here.

00:07:54.059 --> 00:08:00.940
So here I've got one of our development Connect servers, and the gallery is a new tab up at

00:08:00.940 --> 00:08:07.579
the top here, alongside everything else you are familiar with. So I'll go over to the

00:08:07.579 --> 00:08:14.779
gallery, and we've got a bunch of example stuff. So these are, when you log on to Connect,

00:08:14.779 --> 00:08:18.100
you have this window that sometimes pops up unless you tell it to stop popping up that

00:08:18.100 --> 00:08:22.700
has example content. So that all lives here now, and you can deploy it with a single click

00:08:22.700 --> 00:08:27.619
of a button. But I'm going to go over to extensions, and I'm going to install the runtime

00:08:27.619 --> 00:08:34.260
version scanner. So I'm just going to click the add button here, and it'll deploy, hopefully

00:08:34.260 --> 00:08:44.380
quickly. And I can click this button to open it. Actually, the first thing that it's going

00:08:44.380 --> 00:08:51.700
to do is it's going to give me a pop-up, and it'll ask me to add this visitor API key integration

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:58.380
by clicking this button. Now what this does is it allows this app to use the credentials

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:03.099
of whoever's viewing it. So if I shared the URL for this app with someone else who didn't

00:09:03.099 --> 00:09:09.020
have, say, my permissions, because I'm an admin on this server, this, and I don't necessarily

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:13.700
want them to see all the content on the server, this will let it assume the role whoever is

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:29.460
looking at it. I'll just click it, and it'll add it and restart. And so it's going to load

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:36.260
my content, and now I've got a list of everything that I've deployed to the server, along with

00:09:36.260 --> 00:09:43.140
the version of R, Python, and Quarto it runs. And I can check a box here to filter for Python

00:09:43.219 --> 00:09:49.859
By default, the R and Python filters use the tidyverse end-of-life or the official Python

00:09:49.859 --> 00:09:56.580
end-of-life versions, but we can click the drop-down to select from any version that's

00:09:56.580 --> 00:10:04.260
detected on the server. So if I want to pick the lowest version of Python 3.10 on the server,

00:10:04.260 --> 00:10:09.580
I can see anything running below that. And say I'm only interested in updating applications

00:10:09.580 --> 00:10:16.539
and APIs, stuff that's used interactively, I can filter for that too. And if I care about

00:10:16.539 --> 00:10:22.380
view counts in the last quarter, I can select that too. I can download a CSV of my filtered

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:29.500
data. So if I want to monitor this bit of this, say that was a really important dashboard,

00:10:29.500 --> 00:10:37.059
it's critical for it to not go down, I'll set up the content health monitor. And so this

00:10:37.059 --> 00:10:45.940
one is going to take, it has some post-deployment steps because we need to tell it what to monitor.

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:53.659
And then we need to also tell it what schedule to run on. And so after it is deployed and

00:10:53.659 --> 00:11:08.419
renders for the first time, I'll just let that happen. We'll go here. And so it has

00:11:08.419 --> 00:11:12.140
instructions on how to set it up, but I already know how to do that, so I'm not going to make

00:11:12.140 --> 00:11:17.859
you read them. I need to create an environment variable called monitored content, and it

00:11:17.859 --> 00:11:23.659
asks me for the GUID of the content I want to monitor, or just the URL. So I'll go over

00:11:23.659 --> 00:11:37.419
to the runtime version scanner, I'll copy the URL here, and paste in the URL and save

00:11:37.419 --> 00:11:45.979
it. And then I'm going to hit the render button up here. And so when I do that, it's going

00:11:45.979 --> 00:11:53.940
to go check this piece of content, and it will see if it can reach it. And so what it's

00:11:53.940 --> 00:11:59.900
doing is it's checking for an HTTP 200 status, basically. But you can actually, I'll describe

00:11:59.900 --> 00:12:05.979
more how you can configure this to check anything about this content. So if you want to have

00:12:05.979 --> 00:12:13.859
a more detailed check, as opposed to just the web page is reachable. And so yeah, this

00:12:14.460 --> 00:12:20.020
passed, so that's great. We can run it. Or we, this, you know, we can, that other piece of

00:12:20.020 --> 00:12:27.059
content ran successfully. And so I'm going to create a schedule for it. Render on a schedule.

00:12:27.059 --> 00:12:32.900
And I'm going to enable send email after update. It's only going to email me if it fails. So

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:39.940
now that I've done this, this is going to render every day at 12 o'clock PM, and if it

00:12:40.020 --> 00:12:44.900
fails, if the content that is pointed at fails the check, it's going to send an email.

00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:54.099
So those are two extensions, and that's sort of an overview of the gallery. I just have a few

00:12:54.099 --> 00:12:59.700
more slides. So just a few other quick points about the stuff that's in the gallery. So it's

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:07.460
not just app maintenance tools. So we also have some experimental LLM content. We have a sort of

00:13:07.460 --> 00:13:12.739
chat with your content tool, and we have a publisher command center. So it's sort of an

00:13:12.739 --> 00:13:22.739
alternative view of your published apps and running processes. And the stuff that's available

00:13:22.739 --> 00:13:28.419
in the gallery, the updates and new things that we add to the gallery, will appear there and be

00:13:28.419 --> 00:13:34.580
available to install without you needing to update your Connect server. And so I guess the other

00:13:34.580 --> 00:13:43.619
point here is that these are all just like apps and reports that we've written. So anything that

00:13:43.619 --> 00:13:48.099
you can do with the stuff that you've published, you can do with these. So that includes like

00:13:48.099 --> 00:13:53.380
access controls, you know, you can add collaborators so other people who are on your Connect server

00:13:53.380 --> 00:14:01.700
can view them, and you can also download the code behind them. And actually all of this is

00:14:01.700 --> 00:14:11.380
open source. So all this is in a repo on GitHub. And I'll put the URL in bigger text in a second.

00:14:12.739 --> 00:14:19.140
And so you can take any of the code and customize it for your own needs. You can also see how we're

00:14:19.140 --> 00:14:25.059
using our own SDKs and Connect APIs to build all this stuff. Maybe it'll inspire you to make your

00:14:25.140 --> 00:14:32.340
own tools. So for example, the content health monitor, the way that you would customize it to

00:14:32.340 --> 00:14:37.780
do your own check is it's got some instructions in the readme and then a place in the code which

00:14:37.780 --> 00:14:43.140
is sort of an anchor point for you to run any custom checks, health checks on your own content.

00:14:45.940 --> 00:14:53.380
And here's that URL bigger. So the Connect extensions repo in the PositDev organization.

00:14:55.059 --> 00:14:59.299
And we'd love to hear from you. We're interested in learning about the kinds of things that you

00:14:59.299 --> 00:15:03.780
would be interested to see as extensions in the gallery. We're interested in hearing about your

00:15:03.780 --> 00:15:11.059
challenges with workflows maintaining long-lived apps. And yeah, I'm going to be over in the

00:15:11.059 --> 00:15:16.580
Connect booth this afternoon, so you can come find me or any of my colleagues. Yeah, we're very

00:15:16.580 --> 00:15:23.539
interested to hear. Yeah, so that's my demo session. Thanks again.

