I have a question.

00:16:51.859 --> 00:16:59.619
So for your end of life monitoring, is there situations where you would recommend people

00:16:59.619 --> 00:17:03.219
remove Python packages? Because when I think about Connect, I put the code there and it's

00:17:03.219 --> 00:17:05.060
going to live forever because it's so isolated.

00:17:05.060 --> 00:17:05.699
Yeah.

00:17:05.699 --> 00:17:08.339
And I'm just wondering, with this monitoring perspective,

00:17:09.219 --> 00:17:13.619
is the guidance that we should remove old versions of Python?

00:17:13.619 --> 00:17:16.420
I don't think we have specific guidance about that.

00:17:16.420 --> 00:17:21.380
There are different organizations run their Connect servers differently, and sometimes

00:17:22.339 --> 00:17:25.540
we'll have servers that remove an old version of Python.

00:17:25.540 --> 00:17:27.060
But I don't think that's something that...

00:17:27.619 --> 00:17:28.339
Okay.

00:17:28.339 --> 00:17:28.660
Yeah.

00:17:28.660 --> 00:17:33.939
I wouldn't say that the presence of the extension implies guidance that you should be doing that.

00:17:33.939 --> 00:17:34.579
I wouldn't say that.

00:17:34.579 --> 00:17:37.219
I guess I'm slightly concerned that my organization will think that now.

00:17:37.939 --> 00:17:38.180
Okay.

00:17:40.739 --> 00:17:45.619
Because that would actually cost a lot of work for older times, for older apps.

00:17:45.619 --> 00:17:45.780
Yeah.

00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:46.900
Because people need to go through...

00:17:46.900 --> 00:17:47.699
Exactly.

00:17:47.699 --> 00:17:51.459
So yeah, you don't necessarily need to remove old versions of Python from Connect.

